This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

3:01 PM Defendant Scott B Bohlinger in court.  Attorney Walter Arthur Piel Jr. in court for Scott B Bohlinger.  Attorney C. Remington McConnell in court for State of Wisconsin.  Court states case and parties state appearances.  Parties ready to proceed w/motion hearing today.  State calls Off. Christopher Gallagher - RPD - S&T.  Witness ID's DE.  Record to reflect ID of DE.  Exhibit #1 marked and ID'd.  Court receives #1.  State shows/plays part of exhibit #1 (from 1:05 to 3:25).  Atty Piel does cross-exam.  Witness excused.  State makes argument.  Atty Piel makes argument.  Court asks for response from Atty Piel.  Atty Piel responds.  Court denies the motion to suppress.  Court addresses motion to admit statement.  Atty Piel doesn't object so the Court grants that motion.  Court addresses the State's motions in limine that were filed.  Atty Piel has no objection to 1-10.  Court grants 1-10.  Court addresses further motions if the DE should testify.  Parties agree the convictions answer would be three (3).  Court notes the JT is set for 10/19.  State notes they are #2 for 10/19 for the analyst but #1 for 10/20.  Atty Piel doesn't think there are any further motions necessary between now and JT.  State is in agreement and makes record re: edited copy of video being presented to Atty Piel prior to trial.  Atty Piel is in agreement.  Court will begin w/o the jury at 8:30 on 10/19.  Court is adjourned.
